Notice that from its current square (E5) the black queen has a clear diagonal path toward C3 (since D4 is empty) where a white pawn stands. Thus, as Black I will play:

  make_move e5c3

This move (in UCI notation) captures the white pawn on C3 and delivers check.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, I’d like to initiate some forcing play. One idea I’m considering is to bring the queen from g3 to f4, which is a one‐step diagonal move. On f4 the queen lands on the fourth rank (with the white king on e4 already sitting on that rank) and so immediately gives check. Moreover, by landing on f4 the queen’s control of the diagonals (she would then hit f4→e5→d6… and f4→e3→d2→c1, etc.) and her horizontal and vertical reach helps restrict the white king’s escape routes. (For example, with the queen on f4 the white king’s adjacent squares are severely limited: moves to f3, d4, f4, e5 or f5 would run into her fire or into the bishop on d6—which already eyes e5 and f4 via its “down‐right” diagonal.) In many lines the white king will be forced to retreat (say to d3 or d5), after which Black can look for further decisive checks.

So I am going to play the move:

make_move g3f4

In particular, moving it to f5 (that is, 1…Bf5) is appealing. The bishop’s path—c8 → d7 → e6 → f5—is clear, and once on f5 it eyes the diagonal that runs f5–e4–d3–c2, which may come into play soon and even pressure White’s setup after, say, a later capture on e4. It also adheres to solid opening principles by developing a piece to an active square and helping Black contend in the center, which is important since material is even (aside from earlier exchanges) and every tempo counts.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one promising idea is to improve the activity of Black’s a8–rook. Moving it to b8 will immediately put pressure on White’s queenside—especially on the b2‐pawn, which is only defended by the bishop on c1. In many positions if Black’s knight on c4 later jumps in to capture on b2, the rook on b8 is perfectly placed to join the action. Hence a natural, non‐committal developing move that keeps the extra knight intact is

  a8b8

I’ll now make that move.

make_move a8b8

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll choose a forcing move. I notice that my knight on c1 can jump to b3 and deliver an immediate check. In detail, the knight on c1 has these options: a2, b3, d3, and e2. Among these, only  b3  gives check because from b3 the knight attacks d2—the square where the white king sits. (Recall that a knight on b3 attacks a5, c5, d4, d2, a1, and c1.) This check forces white to respond immediately (either by moving the king or by capturing the knight, as the bishop on a4 can reach b3), and it may lead to favorable play if white’s response creates further weaknesses.

So, I will make the move: 

make_move c1b3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

After reviewing the position, I want to play an active, tactical move. I’ll move my knight on f6 into the center with 1…Nf6e4. This move not only puts my knight on an aggressive square but also creates the threat of a fork on f2 (attacking both the white king on d3 and the rook on h1) if I’m allowed to follow up with Nxf2 on my next turn.

If White accepts the sacrifice by capturing with the king, I can recapture with my knight from g5, keeping the material balance while leaving White’s king exposed in the center. If White avoids the capture, the fork threat on f2 forces them to address it, giving me the initiative.

With that reasoning, I’ll now play the move:

make_move f6e4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one idea is to take advantage of the fact that your knight on f2 is currently blocking your dark‐squared bishop’s line toward white’s knight on g1. By moving that knight with a capture, you not only win a pawn but also “unmask” the bishop’s pressure on g1. For example, playing

  make_move f2g4

captures the white pawn on g4 and removes the piece from f2 so that, on the next turn, your bishop on d4 will have a clear diagonal (d4–e3–f2–g1) attacking white’s knight on g1. White will have to move that knight (since its options are limited to e2, f3, or h3) and in many lines you’ll be able to win additional material.

I’ll now play

  make_move f2g4

After Qc8+, the only possible escape for the white king appears to be to h7 (since f8, h8, g7, and f7 are covered by our queen and our king on f6). (White has no way to block or capture—the king must move.)

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, I notice that your knight sitting on d3 is under the long‐range “sight” of the white bishop on b5 along the diagonal b5–c4–d3. (The bishop on b5 would normally deliver check or win material if unchallenged; fortunately, its path to the black king on e8 is blocked by your bishop on d7.) Nonetheless, if you don’t address the knight’s vulnerability, White can simply capture it on a later move.

One natural solution is to save the knight by relocating it to a safe and active square. For example, moving the knight from d3 to c5 (i.e. “d3c5” in UCI notation) does the trick:
 • It gets the knight off the dangerous d3 square.
 • From c5 the knight is centralized and will later pressure sensitive squares like d7 and e6.
 • It avoids any future tactical problems with the white bishop on b5.

Thus, my recommended move is:

make_move d3c5

This move (h3g4) places the bishop on a diagonal that immediately checks the white king on e2 (since from g4 the bishop eyes the down‐left diagonal: f3, e2, d1). It forces the white king to move without giving white an opportunity to block or interpose, and it keeps our pieces well coordinated without risking an unnecessary trade.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one move stands out as a tactical opportunity. Notice that White’s bishop on g5 (on the square g5 of rank 5) isn’t defended by any other White piece. Meanwhile, your knight sitting on e4 has a legal “L‐shaped” jump to g5. By playing

  make_move e4g5

you capture the loose bishop on g5. This wins material (exchanging your knight for White’s bishop—an even trade in point value at best, but here you’re seizing a free piece) and also removes a piece that was eyeing the sensitive d8–e7 diagonal toward your queen.

Before committing, it’s worth double–checking:
• The knight on e4 indeed can jump to g5 (two files right and one rank up).
• After Nxe4g5, White has no immediate recapture since neither knight nor queen can legally take on g5 because the pawn on f2 and other White pieces are too far to help.

Thus,  make_move e4g5 appears to be an excellent, active move for Black.

I’ll now play:

make_move e4g5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll choose to deliver a forcing check. My move will be:

make_move f1d1

This moves my rook from f1 to d1. Notice that after Rf1–d1, the white king on d2 is in check along the d‐file. Furthermore, the rook is defended by my bishop on b3 (since b3–c2–d1 forms a diagonal), so white cannot capture the rook with the king.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position and noticing that the rook on e5 is currently “pinning” the white bishop’s diagonal from b2 to g7 (its presence on e5 is preventing the bishop from checking the king), moving the rook off e5 would immediately expose the king to a discovered check. (That’s why moves like e5f5 or any rook move that leaves e5 were rejected as illegal.)

A good way to resolve this delicate situation is to move the king off that dangerous diagonal. From g7 the king has several candidate moves. However, note that the white bishop on b2 controls the diagonal b2–c3–d4–e5–f6–g7–h8. In order not to walk into check, the king must leave this diagonal.

Evaluating the options:
 • Moving to h8 is not allowed because h8 is on the bishop’s diagonal.
 • Moves to f6 are also forbidden, since f6 is on the diagonal.
 • That leaves moves such as g7→f8, g7→g8, g7→f7, or g7→h6.

Among these, the move g7→g8 (UCI: g7g8) is natural—it moves the king to safety (away from the bishop’s diagonal) while keeping the position solid. Once the king is on g8, the rook on e5 is no longer forced to remain on that diagonal and Black can begin to mobilize the extra material.

Therefore, I’ll play:

(make_move g7g8)

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, a very promising candidate is to activate your knight from g4 with a check. In particular, moving the knight from g4 to f2 (i.e. "g4f2") gives immediate check against the white king on h3. Notice that from f2 the knight attacks h3 (among other squares) so that 1...Nf2+ forces white’s king to move, potentially exposing further weaknesses around the already exposed king. 

For this reason, I’ll now proceed with that move.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll play 1...Nd3e1. This move uses the knight on d3 to capture the white knight sitting on e1. Notice that although white’s king on e2 might seem able to recapture on e1, doing so would be illegal because the square e1 is covered along the g3–f2–e1 diagonal by my bishop on g3. In short, white cannot remove my knight from e1 without moving into check, so this capture wins material. 

(make_move d3e1)

Based on the position and some candidate moves, I’d choose to bring the knight from b4 into d3. This move (b4d3) is a forcing fork—it checks the white king on e1 while also eyeing the pieces on f4 (the white knight) and c1 (the light‐squared bishop), and even touches on the pawn on f2. In many lines white is forced either to capture on d3 or to move the king, both of which often lead to further tactics in Black’s favor. (For example, if White recaptures with the knight from f4, Black can reply with ...exd3, opening lines and further improving the pawn structure while remaining materially ahead.)

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, it turns out that White’s bishop on f5 is giving check along the diagonal f5–e6–d7–c8, with our king on c8 being attacked. (No piece besides our king can capture that bishop, and the only means to parry the check is to block one of the in‐between squares or move the king.) 

Looking at our options:

1. We can block the diagonal by moving the pawn on e7 to e6. (That would place our pawn on e6, interposing between the bishop and the king. However, after …e7e6 the bishop could potentially capture our pawn, and we’d be giving material away.)

2. We could interpose with the rook by playing …d8d7. (But that invites White’s bishop to capture our rook, which would be even worse.) 

3. Finally, we can move our king. (Our king on c8 can only legally move to squares not under attack. Among its neighbors the only safe option is b8.)

After checking the neighbors of c8, we see that b8 is empty and is not attacked by any enemy piece. (Neither White’s knight on f3 nor the other White pieces cover that square.) 

Thus, the most solid response is to move our king from c8 to b8, getting out of check without sacrificing material.

I will now make the move:

make_move c8b8

Black’s pieces are well‐placed. In particular, the knight sitting on c6 can immediately seize the opportunity to win material by capturing the lone white pawn on a5. (That pawn isn’t defended by any piece; white’s knight on b1 does not cover a5, and none of white’s other pieces help there.) Although a natural resource for white might be to try and harass the knight with a queen move (for example Qa4 attacking from a distance), the knight still finds a safe retreat (for instance a jump to c4 is available that — due to white’s own pawn on b4 blocking a direct capture — keeps the knight safe). Winning a pawn is a concrete gain and helps solidify Black’s slight edge.

Thus, my chosen move is to capture on a5 with the knight from c6. In UCI format that move is:

make_move c6a5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play 1...d7d5.

This move not only stakes a claim in the center but also prevents the very dangerous fork that White’s knight on d5 would deliver by hopping to c7 (attacking both the king on e8 and the rook on a8). With 1...d7d5 the d-file is opened so that if White does try 2.Nxc7+ then I can recapture immediately with my queen, nullifying the fork and leaving me with a favorable exchange.
